  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over the past century. Here's a brief overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering efforts date back to the 1920s during Prohibition in the United States\n- Initial focus was on combating organized crime and preventing criminal enterprises from profiting from illegal activities\n\n2. Key Milestone Legislation:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive U.S. law requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Criminalized money laundering as a federal crime in the United States\n\n3. International Development:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Created international standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n- Developed comprehensive global framework for anti-money laundering regulations\n\n4. Post-9/11 Expansion:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements and created stricter enforcement mechanisms\n- Enhanced focus on terrorism financing prevention\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Growing technological sophistication of regulations\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Expanded regulations addressing cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve in response to changing financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
